Image formation

A computer image is a matrix (a two-dimensional (2D) array) of pixels. The value of each pixel is proportional to the brightness of the corresponding point in the scene; its value is, of course, usually derived from the output of an Analog to digital(A/D) converter. We can define a square image as N x N m-bit pixels, where N is the number of points and m controls the number of brightness values. Using m bits gives a range of 2m values, ranging from 0 to 2m - 1. If m is 8, this gives brightness levels ranging between 0 and 255, which are usually displayed as black and white, respectively, with shades of grey in between, as they are for the greyscale image of a scene in application:
 

Following procedures to show the effects of m bits on image:

  1. Convert your color (RGB) image to gray scale.

  2. Obtain the statistical function e.g (median of the gray scale image).

  3. Choose a threshold slider from 0 to 100 e.g (value either 33% above the median.

Signal to noise ratio: SNR or signal-to-noise ratio is the ratio between the desired information or the power of a signal and the undesired signal or the power of the background noise. The ideal value of m is actually related to the signal to noise ratio (dynamic range) of the camera using the application to test it

2D conics. There are other algebraic curves that can be expressed with simple polynomial homogeneous equations. For example, the conic sections (so called because they arise as the intersection of a plane and a 3D cone) can be written using a quadric equation. 3D Lines: Lines in 3D are less elegant than either lines in 2D or planes in 3D. One possible representation is to use two points on the line, (p,q)(p, q)(p,q). Any other point on the line can be expressed as a linear combination of these two points.

3D Quadrics: The 3D analog of a conic section is a quadric surface.

Projective (Perspective transformation): This transformation is particularly useful in tasks such as image registration, 3D reconstruction, and augmented reality. It estimates the homography matrix, which describes how points in one image correspond to points in another image.

Homography: Homography is a 3x3 matrix that maps the points in one image to the corresponding points in another image. Since this matrix has eight degrees of freedom, at least four pairs of points are required to compute the homography.

3D Transformations

Translation: 3D translations can be written as x=x+tx' = x + tx=x+t.

Rotation + Translation: 3D rigid body motion or the 3D Euclidean transformation can be written as x=Rx+tx' = Rx + tx=Rx+t.

Scaled Rotation: The 3D similarity transform can be expressed as x=sRx+tx' = sRx + tx=sRx+t where sss is an arbitrary scale factor.

Affine: The affine transform is written as x=Axx' = \mathbf{A}\bar{x}x=Ax, where A\mathbf{A}A is an arbitrary 343 \times 434 matrix.

Projective: A 3D perspective transform, homography, or collineation operates on homogeneous coordinates.

3D Rotations

If the rotations are known to be a set of uni-axial transforms, they can always be represented using an explicit set of rigid transformations. Rotation about an arbitrary axis. There are three kinds of arbitrary rotation, where we can rotate an object parallel (or along) a specific axis so that the coordinate about which the object rotates remains unchanged and the other two coordinates change. The three kinds of such rotations are possible:

  • Rotation about the x-axis
  • Rotation about the y-axis
  • Rotation about the z-axis

3D Rotation

  • Axis/angle (exponential twist)
  • Unit quaternions

The axis/angle representation is minimal and does not require any additional constraints on the parameters (no need to re-normalize after each update). If the angle is expressed in degrees, it is easier to understand the pose (e.g., 90 twist around the x-axis) and to express exact rotations. When the angle is in radians, the derivatives of RRR with respect to \omega can easily be computed. Quaternions, on the other hand, are better if you want to keep track of a smoothly moving camera, since there are no discontinuities in the representation. It is also easier to interpolate between rotations and to chain rigid transformations.

3D to 2D projections

The more commonly used model is perspective, since this more accurately models the behavior of real cameras. Orthography and para-perspective, An orthographic projection simply drops the z component of the three-dimensional coordinate p to obtain the 2D point x. Orthography is an approximate model for long focal length (telephoto) lenses and objects whose depth is shallow relative to their distance to the camera. Perspective projections are used by artist for drawing three-dimensional scenes.

Photometric image formation

Lighting: Images cannot exist without light. To produce an image, the scene must be illuminated with one or more light sources

Reflectance and Shading: When light hits an objects surface, it is scattered and reflected. Many different models have been developed to describe this interaction. The models are the bidirectional reflectance distribution function, the diffuse, specular, Di-chromatic reflection model, Phong shading models and Global illumination

Digital camera

The main factors affecting the performance of a digital image sensor are the shutter speed(controls the amount of light reaching the sensor), sampling pitch(the physical spacing between adjacent sensor cells on the imaging chip), fill factor(the active sensing area size as a fraction of the theoretically available sensing area), chip size, analog gain, sensor noise, and the resolution (and quality) of the analog-to-digital converter.

Color:

Color is the perceptual result of light in the visible region of the spectrum, having wavelengths in the region of 400  nm to 700  nm, incident upon the retina. Physical power (or radiance) is expressed in a spectral power distribution (SPD), often in 31 components each representing a 10  nm band. Intensity is a measure over some interval of the electromagnetic spectrum of the flow of power. Intensity is what I call a linear-light measure. The standard SI unit for luminous intensity is the candela (cd). Brightness is defined by the CIE as the attribute of a visual sensation according to which an area appears to emit more or less light. Color Specification Systems, there are different types of color system used such as RGB, CMYK, HSV and YIQ.  RGB is the most common color model used in Digital image processing and openCV.  CMYK color model is widely used in printers(-RGB=CMY), HSV uses color in the way humans perceive them. YIQ is the most widely color model used in Television broadcasting.

 

While RGB and CIE RGB and XYZ, and L a b color space are the primary color spaces used to describe the spectral content of color signals, a variety of other representations have been developed both in video and still image coding and in computer graphics
